  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "The phrase \"revert back\" is commonly used in conversation, but it is technically considered redundant. \"Revert\" already means to return to a previous state or condition, so adding \"back\" is unnecessary. A more precise phrase would simply be \"revert.\" However, since it has become widely accepted in informal usage, you may hear it frequently, even in formal settings like the BBC. If you want to be grammatically precise, it's best to use just \"revert.\"",
